      <hedline>
        <hl1>To Heal the Poor of the World</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Letter from Derek Link says there is no alternative to free-market system of drug development, although drug industry could be more charitable to needs of developing countries</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>The drug industry could be more charitable (front page, May 21), but I see no alternative to a free-market system of drug development. Without the chance of big financial rewards, no one would invest billions in risky drug discovery.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>The drug industry could be more charitable (front page, May 21), but I see no alternative to a free-market system of drug development. Without the chance of big financial rewards, no one would invest billions in risky drug discovery.</p>
        <p>Treatment in poor countries is a question of subsidy. Will rich countries increase their aid budgets? Will countries dismantle their armies to help the afflicted? Will Americans accept higher drug prices to subsidize those who can't afford treatment? Recent history suggests the honest answer is no.</p>
        <p>DEREK LINK  Astoria, Queens, May 21, 2000</p>
      </block>
